  "Fluctuates randomly": "",
  "Increases": "",
  "Decreases": "",
  "Stays constant": "",
  "Temperature decreases in the troposphere at an average rate of about 6.5 degrees Celsius per kilometer, known as the environmental lapse rate, because the surface absorbs solar radiation and heats the air above it.": "",
  "The ozone layer is located in the:": "",
  "The ozone layer resides in the stratosphere at approximately 15 to 35 km altitude, where ozone molecules absorb harmful ultraviolet radiation from the Sun and protect life on Earth's surface.": "",
  "Oxygen makes up approximately what percentage of the atmosphere?": "",
  "10%": "",
  "78%": "",
  "21%": "",
  "50%": "",
  "Oxygen comprises approximately 21% of Earth's atmosphere, making it the second most abundant gas after nitrogen and essential for the respiration of most living organisms.": "",
  "The coldest temperatures in the atmosphere are found at the top of the:": "",
  "The mesopause, at the top of the mesosphere (around 85 km altitude), experiences the coldest temperatures in the atmosphere, dropping to approximately negative 90 degrees Celsius.": "",
  "Auroras (Northern and Southern Lights) occur in the:": "",
  "Auroras form in the thermosphere when charged particles from the solar wind interact with atmospheric gases, causing them to emit light at altitudes of roughly 100 to 300 km.": "",
  "At sea level, atmospheric pressure is approximately:": "",
  "500 mb": "",
  "1,013 mb": "",
  "100 mb": "",
  "2,000 mb": "",
  "Standard atmospheric pressure at sea level is 1,013.25 millibars (or 1 atmosphere, or 29.92 inches of mercury), which represents the weight of the entire column of air above that point.": "",
  "Atmospheric pressure _____ with increasing altitude.": "",
  "Increases then decreases": "",
  "Atmospheric pressure decreases with altitude because there is less air above a given point at higher elevations, meaning less weight pressing down and therefore less pressure.": "",
  "The exosphere is the atmospheric layer that:": "",
  "Has the most weather when applying": "",
  "Contains the ozone when measured under": "",
  "Gradually transitions into the vacuum of outer space": "",
  "Is the densest, particularly regarding": "",
  "The exosphere is the outermost layer of the atmosphere, beginning at about 500 to 1,000 km altitude, where gas molecules are so sparse that they can escape into space without colliding with other molecules.": "",
  "What is the tropopause?": "",
  "The warmest region of the atmosphere": "",
  "The boundary between the troposphere and the stratosphere": "",
  "The boundary between the stratosphere and the mesosphere": "",
  "The lowest point of the atmosphere": "",
  "The tropopause is the boundary layer between the troposphere and the stratosphere, located at approximately 8 to 16 km altitude depending on latitude, where the temperature stops decreasing with altitude.": "",
  "What is the greenhouse effect?": "",
  "The hole in the ozone layer caused by pollution": "",
  "The cooling of Earth by ice sheets reflecting sunlight": "",
  "The process by which atmospheric gases trap infrared radiation emitted by Earth's surface, warming the planet": "",
  "The heating of the atmosphere by direct contact with the Sun": "",
  "The greenhouse effect occurs when gases like water vapor, carbon dioxide, and methane absorb and re-emit infrared radiation from Earth's surface, trapping heat and keeping the planet about 33 degrees Celsius warmer than it would be otherwise.": "",
  "What does the term 'lapse rate' refer to in atmospheric science?": "",
  "The rate at which atmospheric pressure drops over time": "",
  "The rate at which temperature changes with altitude": "",
  "The rate at which humidity increases near the surface": "",
  "The speed at which wind decreases with altitude": "",
  "The lapse rate describes how temperature changes with altitude, with the average environmental lapse rate in the troposphere being about 6.5 degrees Celsius of cooling per kilometer of elevation gained.": "",
  "What is Rayleigh scattering?": "",
  "The reflection of sunlight by cloud surfaces": "",
  "The absorption of infrared radiation by greenhouse gases": "",
  "The process by which small atmospheric molecules scatter shorter wavelengths of light more than longer ones": "",
  "The bending of light as it passes through different atmospheric layers": "",
  "Rayleigh scattering occurs when atmospheric gas molecules scatter shorter wavelengths of visible light (blue and violet) more effectively than longer wavelengths, which is why the sky appears blue during the day.": "",
  "What is the ionosphere?": "",
  "The lowest region of the stratosphere containing ozone": "",
  "A layer of volcanic gases in the troposphere": "",
  "A region within the thermosphere where solar radiation ionizes gas molecules, enabling radio wave reflection": "",
  "The boundary between the mesosphere and thermosphere": "",
  "The ionosphere is a region within the thermosphere (and partially the mesosphere) where ultraviolet and X-ray radiation from the Sun ionizes atmospheric gases, creating layers of charged particles that can reflect certain radio frequencies back to Earth.": "",
  "What are CFCs (chlorofluorocarbons)?": "",
  "Synthetic chemicals once used in refrigerants and aerosols that release chlorine atoms which destroy ozone molecules": "",
  "Compounds that form acid rain when mixed with water": "",
  "Natural volcanic gases that warm the atmosphere": "",
  "Carbon-based fuels burned in power plants": "",
  "Chlorofluorocarbons are human-made chemical compounds that were widely used in refrigerants, aerosol propellants, and solvents until it was discovered that they release chlorine atoms in the stratosphere, with a single chlorine atom capable of destroying thousands of ozone molecules.": "",
  "What does the term 'air density' mean?": "",
  "The mass of air per unit volume at a given location": "",
  "The amount of water vapor in the air": "",
  "The speed at which air molecules move": "",
  "The temperature of air at a given altitude": "",
  "Air density refers to the mass of air molecules contained within a given volume and is highest at sea level where the weight of the atmosphere above compresses the air, causing more molecules to be packed into each unit of space.": "",
  "What is the Montreal Protocol?": "",
  "An agreement to reduce carbon dioxide emissions from fossil fuels": "",
  "A treaty to limit nuclear testing in the atmosphere": "",
  "A scientific model used to predict future climate change": "",
  "An international treaty adopted in 1987 to phase out ozone-depleting substances such as CFCs": "",
  "The Montreal Protocol (1987) is widely considered one of the most successful environmental treaties in history, as it led to the global phase-out of CFCs and other ozone-depleting chemicals, allowing the ozone layer to gradually recover.": "",
