  "A gas that only appears during volcanic eruptions": "",
  "A gas present in very small concentrations but which can have significant effects on atmospheric processes": "",
  "A gas that has been completely removed from the atmosphere": "",
  "A gas that only exists in laboratory settings": "",
  "Trace gases such as carbon dioxide (about 0.04%), methane, and ozone exist in very small concentrations in the atmosphere but play outsized roles in processes like the greenhouse effect and UV protection.": "",
  "What is a jet stream?": "",
  "A narrow band of strong, high-altitude winds found near the tropopause that influences weather patterns": "",
  "A surface wind pattern that only occurs near coastlines": "",
  "A current of warm water flowing through the ocean": "",
  "A column of rising hot air that forms thunderstorms": "",
  "Jet streams are fast-flowing, narrow bands of wind found at approximately 9 to 12 km altitude near the tropopause, with speeds often exceeding 160 km/h, and they play a major role in steering weather systems across the mid-latitudes.": "",
  "A mountaineer ascending Mount Everest notices breathing becomes increasingly difficult above 5,000 meters. This happens primarily because:": "",
  "Wind speeds at high altitude blow oxygen away from the mountain": "",
  "Oxygen molecules change into a different form at high altitudes": "",
  "The percentage of oxygen in the air drops significantly above 5,000 meters": "",
  "Atmospheric pressure is much lower at that altitude, so each breath contains far fewer oxygen molecules": "",
  "While oxygen remains at about 21% of the air at all altitudes, the much lower atmospheric pressure at 5,000+ meters means the air is far less dense, so each breath delivers significantly fewer oxygen molecules to the lungs.": "",
  "Residents of a coastal city notice that their AM radio station can be heard at much greater distances at night. This is best explained by:": "",
  "Changes in the ionosphere at night allow it to reflect AM radio waves back to Earth over longer distances": "",
  "Cooler nighttime air transmits sound waves more efficiently": "",
  "The troposphere contracts at night, amplifying radio signals": "",
  "Radio stations increase their broadcast power after dark": "",
  "At night, without solar radiation, the lower layers of the ionosphere recombine and effectively disappear, allowing the higher ionospheric layers to reflect AM radio waves over much greater distances than during the daytime.": "",
  "Scientists discover that the ozone hole over Antarctica is slowly recovering. This recovery is most directly attributed to:": "",
  "Warmer global temperatures speeding up ozone production": "",
  "Natural volcanic activity releasing ozone-forming chemicals": "",
  "Increased carbon dioxide absorbing UV radiation before it reaches the stratosphere": "",
  "The global phase-out of CFCs under the Montreal Protocol": "",
  "The gradual recovery of the ozone hole is a direct result of the Montreal Protocol, which banned the production of CFCs and other ozone-depleting substances, allowing stratospheric ozone concentrations to slowly rebuild over decades.": "",
  "A pilot flying at 11,000 meters notices that the temperature outside the aircraft has stopped decreasing and is beginning to rise slightly. The aircraft has most likely entered the:": "",
  "Thermosphere, where auroras occur": "",
