  "Stratosphere, which has very low wind speeds": "",
  "Mesosphere, which has few gas molecules": "",
  "Exosphere, where gas density is so low that molecules rarely collide with the satellite": "",
  "At 800 km altitude, the satellite is in the exosphere where gas molecules are extremely sparse and widely separated, producing negligible atmospheric drag compared to lower thermospheric altitudes where some residual gas density still exists.": "",
  "A city located in a valley frequently experiences severe smog events during winter. The most likely atmospheric condition contributing to this is:": "",
  "Strong convective mixing that brings pollutants to the surface": "",
  "Stratospheric ozone descending into the valley": "",
  "A temperature inversion in which warm air above traps cooler, polluted air near the surface in the valley": "",
  "Extremely low atmospheric pressure pulling pollutants downward": "",
  "Temperature inversions occur when a layer of warm air sits above cooler surface air, preventing vertical mixing and trapping pollutants near the ground, a situation that is especially problematic in valley locations during calm winter conditions.": "",
  "A researcher wants to understand why Earth's average surface temperature is about 15 degrees Celsius rather than the negative 18 degrees Celsius predicted without any atmosphere. The best explanation is:": "",
  "The Sun has become 33 degrees warmer since the atmosphere formed": "",
  "The natural greenhouse effect, in which atmospheric gases absorb and re-emit infrared radiation, raises the surface temperature by about 33 degrees Celsius": "",
  "Friction from atmospheric winds generates enough heat to warm the surface": "",
  "Earth's core generates enough geothermal heat to warm the surface by 33 degrees": "",
  "The approximately 33-degree-Celsius difference between Earth's actual average temperature and the theoretical temperature without an atmosphere is entirely due to the natural greenhouse effect, in which water vapor, CO2, and other gases trap outgoing infrared radiation.": ""
